 to Scanlon and Teitel -- tChapter 19 Human Rights and Democracy in Practice: The Challenge of Accountability -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this important collection of writings, leading legal and political thinkers address a wide array of issues that confront societies undergoing a transition to democratic rule. Bridging the gap between theory and practice in international human rights law and policy, the contributors continue discussions that were begun with the late Argentine philosopher-lawyer Carlos Santiago Nino, then extend those conversations in new directions inspired by their own and Nino’s work.The book focuses on some of the key questions that confront the international human rights movement today. What is the moral justification for the concept and content of universal human rights? What is the relationship among nation-building, constitutionalism, and democracy? What are the political implications for a conception of universal human rights? What is the relationship between moral principles and political practice? How should a society confront what Kant called radical evil? And how does a successor regime justly and practically hold a prior regime accountable for gross violations of human rights?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh1 aCalsamiglia, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDworkin, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell, Martin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiss,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoti, Jaime Malamud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re